sql:
SELECT sequence_id, sequence_name 
FROM sequences 
WHERE recording_duration = (SELECT MAX(recording_duration) FROM sequences);

SELECT COUNT(sequence_id)
FROM sequence_metadata
WHERE LOWER(additional_info) LIKE '%quiet room%';

SELECT AVG(age) AS average_age
FROM speakers
WHERE gender = 'Female' AND age > 30;

external_knowledge:
Active participants refer to users with a status 'active';
Involvement with specific sequences implies a connection between users and particular speech sequences;
The statistical measure of their performance is indicated by LLRMean, a metric that evaluates the effectiveness or quality of their contribution to the sequence;
The query presumably intended to link user IDs to sequence IDs and result IDs through correct join conditions to fulfill these criteria.

- 'older speaker' refers to speakers over the age of 50;
- 'considered quite favorable' means the sequence description contains 'good';
- 'specific method' is the processing method named 'VM';
- 'high intelligibility score' is above 0.6;
- 'significant signal quality' indicates an SSNR greater than 25;
- 'Unicode value of the sequence name is greater than 1000' ensures the sequence name isn't too common.

